FT  31 JUL 92 / International Company News: Overseas operations and life
side lift AIG
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
AMERICAN International Group, one of the largest US composite insurers,
yesterday reported after-tax profits of Dollars 425.6m in the three months
to end-June, a 6.1 per cent improvement on the same period a year earlier.
The result takes profits for the first six months of 1992 to Dollars 839.5m,
against Dollars 776.4m in the previous year. The figures are scored after
realised investment gains of Dollars 26.5m (against Dollars 31m a year ago)
in the second quarter, and Dollars 54.5m (Dollars 54.6m) for the six months.
Mr Maurice Greenberg, chairman, said the second quarter had been 'reasonably
good' for the company overall. The US property-casualty market continued to
be 'very competitive in most lines of business other than the specialty
classes', and catastrophe losses had been particularly heavy. But life
operations and sizeable overseas operations 'provided a counterbalance'.
General insurance operations made an underwriting loss of Dollars 15.9m in
the six months, compared with a profit of Dollars 41.8m a year earlier. But
higher investment income meant that operating profit fell only 1.5 per cent
to Dollars 599.8m (Dollars 608.8m). Net premiums were Dollars 4.63bn against
Dollars 4.62bn.
The life operations, by contrast, pushed up operating profits by 16 per cent
in the first half, to Dollars 295.2m (Dollars 254.5m). Premium income rose
to Dollars 2.26bn from Dollars 1.91bn.
Transamerica, the San Francisco-based financial services group planning to
divest its property-casualty insurance operations, reported after-tax
profits of Dollars 60.3m for the quarter to end-June against Dollars 55.1m a
year ago. Profits from the businesses which will form the continuing group
rose from Dollars 43m to Dollars 97.5m.
Half-year after-tax profits stand at Dollars 143.9m (Dollars 63m).
