<HEADLINE>
FT  31 JUL 92 / International Company News: BMW advances despite tough
market conditions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WALLER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BMW, the German luxury car manufacturer, yesterday reported net profits up
10.5 per cent to DM421m (Dollars 284m) in the first half of the year.
Against a backdrop of difficult markets in Europe and elsewhere, turnover
climbed by 12 per cent to DM16.2bn and the number of cars sold rose by 15.4
per cent to 300,367.
In the first half, it produced 313,000 cars, 19 per cent more than in the
same period last year.
The company predicted the rate of growth would slow in the second half but
said it would probably manufacture and sell more cars and motorcycles over
1992 as a whole than it did last year, when car output totalled 553,000
units.
BMW attributed its strong performance to its new 3-Series model which, BMW
said, had enjoyed widespread success. This had helped BMW's total car sales
to increase by 30 per cent in the US, to 31,000 models, and to maintain its
sales in Japan at the same level as last year despite sharply deteriorating
conditions.
BMW said a lasting recovery in the world car market could hardly be expected
this year, especially in the light of the uncertain economic recovery in the
US and Japan.
Conditions in Europe - and especially Germany - would remain weak because of
high interest rates. The outlook for the German market was blighted by the
prospect of further taxes, levies and restrictions, the company complained.
It said it was doing its best to ensure profitability would be maintained
despite Germany's unattractiveness as a production location.
It aims to invest some DM500m in the first stage of a plant in South
Carolina which, the company said, would strengthen its international
competitiveness, secure jobs and reduce vulnerability to fluctuations in the
US dollar.
Mercedes-Benz, the luxury car subsidiary of Daimler-Benz, Germany's largest
industrial company, has signed letters of intent to set up joint venture
production facilities in Kazakhstan, Uzbekistan and Turkmenistan.
Mr Werner Niefer, chief executive, said he had arranged the sale of a large
number of Mercedes vehicles in all three countries.
</TEXT>
