FT  31 JUL 92 / Tories accused of 'betraying' jobless
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR launched a fresh attack on the government's record on jobs yesterday
when it claimed that the Tories had failed to deliver 10,000 promised places
on their Employment Action programme.
The onslaught was a first shot in the opposition's promised summer offensive
on the economy. It came when three members of the shadow economic team
charged the government with a 'callous betrayal' of the unemployed.
Labour said in a statement released by Mr Gordon Brown, shadow chancellor,
that Mr Michael Howard, when employment secretary, had committed the
government to finding work experience places for 60,000 people and to having
30,000 people on schemes at any time.
Yet in May, two months after a target deadline had been passed, some 10,000
places had remained unfilled. 'In many constituencies there are as many as
10,000 people unemployed, with sometimes as few as 30 places on Employment
Action available,' the statement said. It was also signed by Mr Frank
Dobson, shadow employment secretary, and Ms Harriet Harman, shadow chief
secretary to the Treasury.
