<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JUL 92 / London Stock Exchange: Equity futures and options trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PRICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BUYERS returned to the stock index futures as both technical and market
factors combined to cause a surge in a busy session, writes Christopher
Price.
The September contract on the FT-SE opened weakly, at 2,399, as traders were
lulled into believing that Tuesday's bounce in the market was a technical
one and that yesterday promised a corresponding downturn. But the strong
equities market was quickly underpinned by a big order from BZW, which
became the signal for other buyers to take advantage of what had been a
sellers' market.
September began to race ahead, tranforming a 10-point fair value discount to
a similar premium within half-an-hour. Many of the small independent traders
were said to be caught short by the buying binge, as were some larger
houses.
The contract continued to be squeezed up into the afternoon session and a
strong Wall Street helped sentiment. September closed at 2,445, up 58 from
its previous finish and around a 10-point premium to its fair value of
around 12.
In traded options, turnover was a brisk 28,240 contracts, a third up from
Tuesday's total. British Airways led the stock options on 1,243 contracts
dealt, with the October 300 series featuring.
