<TEXT>
BETHLEHEM Steel, the second largest US steel manufacturer, yesterday
reported increased second-quarter net losses and warned it expected to
remain in the red in the third quarter.
The company reported net losses of Dollars 64m, or 92 cents a share,
compared with Dollars 29m, or 46 cents a share, in the same period of last
year, on net sales of Dollars 1.0bn, down from Dollars 1.1bn. The results,
which included a Dollars 25m litigation contingency charge, were in line
with a previous warning by the company.
Bethlehem said it expected a moderate improvement in steel demand for the
balance of 1992. An expected improvement in the economy, higher levels of
steel demand and remedies against unfair steel imports should provide
opportunities for improved results later this year and in 1993, it added.
