<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JUL 92 / International Company News: Du Pont lifts underlying profits
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN FRIEDMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
DU PONT, the leading US chemicals company, managed a 3 per cent rise in the
level of its underlying second-quarter net profits.
Although the company's Dollars 440m net income for the quarter was 19.9 per
cent down year-on-year, the profits were actually 3 per cent higher when
extraordinary items were subtracted from the quarterly figures this year and
last.
The 1992 second quarter included a previously announced Dollars 134m
one-time charge for additional costs related to the recall of its Benlate DF
fungicide.
Earnings per share were 65 cents for the quarter, against 81 cents a year
ago. For the first six months of 1992 earnings per share were Dollars 1.36
against Dollars 1.69 in the same period last year.
Revenues in the second quarter were Dollars 9.8bn, an increase of 4 per cent
after adjustments to reflect a new coal venture accounted for under the
equity method.
Combined sales for chemicals, fibres, polymers and diversified businesses
were 3 per cent above last year. Volume was 6 per cent improved, but prices
were down by an average of 3 per cent.
Combined earnings for these businesses were 37 per cent higher, excluding
non-recurring charges.
Earnings from the Conoco energy business were down by 65 per cent, the only
division to suffer an underlying slump. Du Pont attributed this to lower
worldwide refined product margins, an absence of benefits from the kind of
crude oil forward sales achieved in 1991 and lower natural gas prices.
Mr Edgar Woolard, chairman, said a number of Du Pont's businesses were
achieving 'solid sales and earnings growth in spite of an uneven economic
recovery'.
He said the group continued to benefit from improvements in operating costs
and productivity. The resulting gains more than offset the downturn in the
petroleum sector.
Wall Street seemed to agree and reacted favourably to the Du Pont results,
marking the share price Dollars 2 3/4 higher to Dollars 52 3/8 .
Mr William Young, a chemicals industry analyst at Donaldson Lufkin &amp;
Jenrette in New York, said he was impressed by the results: 'I think they
are doing quite well. Volumes are up considerably year-to-year. Their cost
cutting is having a major impact and if you look at the big four chemical
companies in the US, Du Pont is the only one to have an underlying profits
increase.'
</TEXT>
