<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JUL 92 / International Company News: Toyota signals end of a dynasty
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GORDON CRAMB
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
TOYOTA Motor yesterday signalled the end of Japan's most successful
corporate dynasty when it appointed a president from within the founding
Toyoda ( family, but said the next incumbent would probably come from the
group at large.
Mr Tatsuro Toyoda, aged 63, inherits the job from his elder brother
Shoichiro, 67, who becomes chairman. Mr Eiji Toyoda, their 79-year-old
uncle, is relinquishing that post to become honorary chairman.
Tatsuro, a New York University MBA graduate who in 1984 spearheaded the
launch of Toyota's landmark US joint production venture with General Motors,
is expected to bring a more international flavour to the job. He said
yesterday that such a background had helped him win the post.
He added, however, that the speed of technological change dictated that his
presidency of the country's biggest car maker would not be nearly as long as
Shoichiro's 10 years. When asked whether the company's next president would
come from outside the family, he said: 'It is likely.'
The complacent nature of family managements in some large companies is
coming under increasing criticism as a domestic economic slowdown has put
earnings growth into reverse. Mr Shoichiro Toyoda, pointing out that the
Toyodas were not represented in any other senior management levels below the
presidency, held out the prospect of a more collegiate style.
Saying that 'management should not depend on a single leader', he announced
the appointment as vice-chairman of Mr Masami Iwasaki, who along with Mr
Tatsuro Toyoda had been vice-president. Five other directors were made
vice-presidents in their place.
Industry analysts, while cautioning that any changes in strategy were likely
to be modest, said Toyota had to find ways to get to grips with the fall-off
in domestic demand. Mr Koji Endo, of S G Warburg Securities, described
Tatsuro as 'a top-rated executive, even if he is a Toyoda anyway' and one of
the most internationally minded at the company.
However, Toyota has recently become markedly more bullish than its rivals on
car sales in Japan in the rest of calendar 1992. It is predicting that the
worst is over and, after a 4 per cent first-half fall, demand for Toyota
models in the July to December period should be flat.
Some industry watchers attribute the confidence to pending model launches,
and others to aggressive pricing which will cost it earnings previously
taken for granted. Mr Shoichiro Toyoda said the company was sticking to that
forecast although 'recovery was a little lagging behind'.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 23
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT923-10406</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CG3AYAFEFT</PROFILE>
