FT  30 JUL 92 / BT falls 28% as turnover declines
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH Telecommunications' first quarter pre-tax profit fell by 27.8 per
cent after bigger than expected redundancy costs and a loss from the sale of
its controlling stake in Mitel, the Canadian telephone equipment maker.
For the three months to June 30 BT's pre-tax profit fell from Pounds 825m to
Pounds 596m on sales of Pounds 3.27bn, down from Pounds 3.34bn. It was the
first quarter-on-quarter decline in turnover since the company was
privatised in 1984.
An exceptional charge of Pounds 135m relates to the loss made on the
disposal of its interests in Mitel, International Aeradio, its aviation
services subsidiary, and Sharelink, the Birmingham-based stockbroking group.
Operating profits fell from Pounds 920m to Pounds 799m. They were further
depressed by redundancy charges of Pounds 56m due to the early retirement of
29,000 people - 9,000 more than expected - under BT's voluntary redundancy
scheme.
A further Pounds 11m attributable to the restructuring of management has
been set against the provision established in 1990 for this purpose. The
shares yesterday rose 13p to close at 346p as the efforts to control costs
were better than expected.
News of the redundancies overshadowed BT's disappointing trading
performance.
The number of inland calls fell by 3 per cent quarter-on-quarter. Revenue
from international calls rose by 5 per cent, on a 12-month moving average
basis, but this was due more to international calls being routed through
London than an increase in people making calls from the UK.
Mr Iain Vallance, chairman, said: 'The decline in turnover reflects the
continued pressures of the economy, regulation and competition.'
The Office of Telecommunications, the industry regulator, has told BT to cut
the price of a basket of its basic services each year by inflation minus 7.5
percentage points by next August, compared with 6.25 points previously.
BT yesterday said: 'We are cutting costs, but there comes a time when you
cannot squeeze anything else out.'
Strong cash flow in the first quarter, free of dividend or tax payments,
reduced net debt by Pounds 715m to Pounds 1.79bn, representing gearing of 17
per cent. Earnings per share fell from 9p to 5.6p.
