<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JUL 92 / Honecker flown home to face trial
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LESLIE COLITT, QUENTIN PEEL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BERLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE UNDIGNIFIED tug-of-war over Mr Erich Honecker, the former East German
communist leader, ended last night when he was flown from Moscow to Berlin
to face trial for the alleged manslaughter of defectors shot while trying to
escape to the west.
Months of negotiations between Germany, Russia and Chile - in whose Moscow
embassy he took refuge to avoid extradition - came to a head when he was
taken from the embassy to a military aircraft at Moscow's Vnukovo airport.
The 79-year-old hardliner, who led East Germany for 18 years until 1989,
landed at Berlin's heavily guarded Tegel airport and was immediately driven
to Moabit prison.
Two doctors examined Mr Honecker in prison and ruled he was well enough to
withstand jail, a justice official said. After a more thorough examination,
the Berlin district court must decide whether he will remain in jail. He
will appear before a judge today.
The official said Mr Honecker's trial was expected to start 'some time this
year'.
Mr Honecker faces charges of manslaughter in connection with the deaths of
49 East Germans shot while trying to escape to the west between 1961 and
1989.
One question to be answered is whether Mr Honecker is fit to stand trial,
having had an operation for kidney cancer in 1990.
The other doubt concerns the legal basis of charges against him. An 800-page
indictment has been drawn up by the Berlin justice department, accusing Mr
Honecker and five fellow leaders of the communist government of complicity
in the killing of defectors at the Berlin Wall and the border with West
Germany. The problem is to make the charges stick in terms of the law of
East Germany which was prevailing at the time.
The Berlin authorities have levelled the charges on three fronts: that Mr
Honecker and his colleagues, including Mr Erich Mielke, the former head of
the Ministry of State Security (Stasi), exceeded their powers under East
German law; that they broke international laws, in particular the UN
convention on civil rights; and that they infringed basic human rights.
Mr Honecker argues that he cannot be found guilty on that basis, because he
was empowered under East German law to issue administrative orders,
including the order to shoot to kill.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 18
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT923-10417</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CG3AYAE3FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920730
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JUL 92 / The Lex Column: Lasmo
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
By the middle of this decade Lasmo could have entered a golden age.
Development expenditure is peaking; if the disposal programme proceeds
according to plan, gearing should soon start to drop from its present 80 per
cent. Debt should be further reduced within a couple of years as the heavy
oil and gas investments in Indonesia and the North Sea pay off. That could
suggest the shares are undervalued after their fall of more than 60 per cent
during the past year. The snag is that there are still some short-term
hurdles to overcome before long-term promise is fulfilled.
Lasmo has managed to maintain its interim dividend, but it was helped by its
decision to capitalise the Pounds 22m interest costs of carrying Ultramar's
downstream businesses which are now sold. The company would argue that the
move was a logical reflection of the fact that the downstream assets were
never relevant to its main business, but indirectly it still helped relieve
pressure on distributable reserves. More open assistance came from the
release to distributable reserves of Pounds 373m from its merger reserve.
That more than offset the extraordinary loss of Pounds 291m on the
downstream assets disposal.
One interpretation of these balance sheet manoeuvres is that they show the
company's determination to maintain its dividend. But they also underline
the tightness of the distributable reserve position. The company should be
placed to maintain its final payment. Barring a rebound in the sterling
price of oil, next year's prospects are less certain. By then there will be
less scope for capitalising interest on development activities. Lasmo may be
trading close to the lower end of the range of net asset estimates, but the
shares are not for the nervous.
</TEXT>
