<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JUL 92 / The Barcelona Olympics: Boardman races to superbike gold
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER BERLIN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BARCELONA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CHRIS BOARDMAN rode his winged superbike to an Olympic gold medal in the
4,000-metre pursuit final in Barcelona last night.
Boardman struck first gold not only for Britain and himself but also for
Lotus, the Norwich-based sports car company, which developed his monocoque
bicycle with small ground effect wings, where the handles would be on a
normal racing bicycle.
As he stood on the victor's podium in the warm-up area in the middle of the
banked track, the Lotus engineers pressed against nearby railings
photographing the man who had ridden a revolutionary machine to fame.
Boardman, who said afterwards he lacked confidence all week, attacked Jens
Lehmann, his German opponent, from the start. On the first lap of the
250-metre oval, he was a third of a second ahead. By the fourth lap he had
pushed that lead to one second - a sizeable advantage in a race in which one
circuit takes 16 seconds. Another 750 metres and it was 2 seconds, and the
German must have known the race was lost.
The crowd sensed victory was in the Briton's grasp and they roared Boardman
on. With one lap to go the hound caught the hare and Boardman raised his
fist to begin his victory lap early.
In the semi-finals an hour before he had enjoyed an easier passage than his
German opponent. Lehmann was taken to the line by New Zealander Gary
Anderson, winning by 4/10ths of a second in 4 mins 27.23 seconds.
Boardman, in contrast, only rode 4 mins 29.332 seconds, five seconds outside
the world record he had set the night before. Boardman built a 3.5 second
lead over Mark Kingsland of Australia, easing off to win by 2.9 seconds.
</TEXT>
