<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JUL 92 / The Barcelona Olympics: Lotus gears up to peddle innovative
design concept - John Griffiths analyses commercial prospects for the
hi-tech cycle that has fulfilled British Olympic hopes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GRIFFITHS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LOTUS Engineering, the consultancy design and engineering arm of General
Motors' British sports-car subsidiary, is looking for a partner to produce
and distribute a roadgoing form of the 'supercycle' with which Chris
Boardman of the UK has won an Olympic gold medal.
It wants versions of the LotusSport pursuit cycle used by Boardman, known as
the Windcheetah, on world markets by early next year. It would offer a more
traditional riding position but would incorporate the basic concept of a
one-piece moulded monocoque frame.
Failure to do so may risk losing the benefit of the unprecedented publicity
for the machine. 'We could lose the market to makers of replicas which might
look the same but lack its integrity and performance,' Lotus said yesterday.
Lotus plans to build a very limited number of machines over the next few
months at its Group Lotus headquarters in Hethel, Norfolk, which has
extensive facilities created originally for sports car production. The
machines will be built for top competition cyclists and will cost at least
Pounds 5,000 each.
Lotus might go on to build up to 1,000 somewhat less expensive units a year
 -forgoing carbon fibre at Pounds 330 a kilogramme and titanium at Pounds
150 a kilogramme - within its existing facilities.
It is mainly interested in finding a partner to which it can either license
the manufacture of a much higher volume of cheaper machines, a subcontractor
capable of building them - or taking part in a joint venture that might lead
to purpose-built facilities being created at Hethel.
Lotus Engineering does not expect initial derivatives of the 'supercycle' to
be sufficiently cheap to challenge manufacturers such as Raleigh in the
conventional cycle market.
The cycle is seen as presenting a potential challenge both to conventional
racing and quasi-racing cycles and to the fad for 'mountain' bikes.
Lotus lays claim to having done substantial development work on the cycle,
and has invested some Pounds 125,000 in it. But it acquired the rights to
the machine from its creator, Norwich-based engineer Mr Michael Burrows, who
had spent several years trying to interest cycle manufacturers in his
concept.
</TEXT>
