<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JUL 92 / Tories to press ahead on Maastricht ratification
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT intends to press ahead before the end of the year with
ratifying the Maastricht treaty. This in the light of the planned Danish
statement in the autumn on the crisis prompted by its referendum which
rejected the treaty.
The foreign office is keen that the UK should take the initiative on the
Maastricht bill during its presidency of the European Commission, and is
confident that the proposed statement, which is expected about the time of
the Tory conference in October, will enable progress to be made.
Before the Commons rose earlier this month, some ministers were paving the
way for a possible delay in the Maastricht bill to next year, but the
foreign office believes the UK must proceed with ratification during its
presidency if its position is not to be undermined.
While all plans are on a contingency basis until the French referendum on
September 20, ministers have begun discussions about how to handle Tory
rebels. One option being considered is to separate the different strands of
unease about Europe among Tory MPs on issues such as the Exchange Rate
Mechanism, and frontiers.
The idea would be to break up 'Euro-scepticism' as such, and to focus on
difficulties MPs may have with individual aspects of the UK's links with the
rest of the EC.
Apart from hardline Euro-sceptics, Tories who have expressed concern about
those issues may be offered meetings with senior ministers most closely
involved, including Mr Douglas Hurd, foreign secretary, Mr Kenneth Clarke,
home secretary, and Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary.
That move to allay concerns would run alongside a tough parliamentary regime
for the bill itself. A guillotine or timetable motion looks unlikely, since
it would focus opposition among other parties, but votes to curtail
individual debates on proposed amendments to the bill will still be needed.
</TEXT>
