FT  30 JUL 92 / Imbert connects crime with poverty
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD EVANS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SIR Peter Imbert, Metro-politain Police commissioner, yesterday linked an
increase in crime to poverty and social deprivation. Presenting his last
annual report before he retires, Sir Peter said: 'The notion that there is a
link between crime and social deprivation is a compelling one . . . there is
a need to offer hope to those most disadvantaged if we are to see any
reduction in crime levels.'
Sir Peter said that crime in London had increased 11 per cent last year,
largely because the capital was seen as the natural mecca for criminals and
most of the country's wealth was concentrated there.
His report paints a stark picture of crime in the capital that last year
included 75 per cent of the country's drugs market and 75 per cent of
frauds. In addition, London, with a seventh of the country's population,
last year suffered more than 50 per cent of all armed robberies, and 20 per
cent of all murders and rapes.
Sir Peter's report discloses that a total of 945,000 crimes were committed,
a rise of 11 per cent, and 113,000 people were arrested, 3 per cent down on
the previous year.
The 41,000 casualties on London's roads left 369 dead, 7,000 seriously
injured and 34,000 slightly hurt. In addition, 184,000 people and vehicles
were searched resulting in 25,000 arrests.
</TEXT>
