<DATE>920730
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JUL 92 / Print union may test its strength: Casual labour brings the
threat of action
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ST IVES, the second-biggest commercial printer in Britain, is drifting into
a dispute with the GPMU, the print union, which may prove an important test
of union power in the general printing industry.
The issue at St Ives is the use of casual labour. The union objects to the
fact that, to cover for peaks in work flow, St Ives is employing a growing
number of temporary workers in the unskilled finishing area, where magazines
and books are bound and packed.
The dozens of temporary workers hired from employment agencies earn Pounds 3
an hour, compared with the hourly rate for full-time workers of Pounds 5.85.
The dispute is typical at this point in the business cycle. Business remains
too uncertain to increase permanent staffing but surges of work require
extra labour. The pattern will be familiar to managers and union officials
in many other industries.
But, for the printing industry, it may have an additional significance. The
breaking of union power in the national newspaper industry in the 1980s did
not, on the surface, spread to the general printing industry.
Some analysts, however, believe that a combination of labour law reforms,
technological change and recession has 'hollowed out' union power in general
printing, too, over the past few years.
It is true that industrial disputes have been rare in the 1990s, and print
managers have generally got what they wanted on flexibility and on changing
working practices, especially in machine rooms.
Union derecognition has been rare, though. Print workers remain among the
best organised and best paid in the country - at St Ives, the average
shopfloor worker earns Pounds 25,000, according to the company. The
perishability of their product, at least in sectors such as magazines, still
gives the unions industrial clout. Moreover, the merger of two leading print
unions to form the GPMU may also help in resisting the hostile trends.
To date, print managers have not tested the hypothesis that union power has
crumbled. BPCC, Britain's biggest printer, did provoke a rash of disputes
earlier this year as it attempted to reduce overcapacity.
Yet the union claims to have emerged unscathed and, on the crucial issue of
casualisation, it says that BPCC agreed to pay temporary workers the same as
full-time workers.
St Ives, one of the most union-friendly companies in the industry, is run by
Mr Bob Gavron, an urbane Labour supporter, and is not cut out to be the News
International of the general printing industry.
The company said yesterday: 'We don't want to pick a fight with the union,
but we need temporary labour because of the nature of the work flow and we
don't want to pay more than the market rate for it.' The company adds that
it has gone to great lengths to keep its 3,000 full-time staff through the
recession, even when there has not been enough work for many of them.
Mr Tony Dubbins, leader of GPMU, is not impressed. He believes that St Ives
has taken a decision to 'casualise' the finishing area and that, if it
succeeds, the rest of the industry will follow.
Hence the 1,000 GPMU members who work in the seven St Ives web-offset plants
 -printing magazines such as The Economist, Company and New Woman - will
next week start to ballot on industrial action. Initially they will be
balloted on taking action short of a strike - an overtime ban. If that does
not bite, St Ives may face the most serious printing strike for years.
Will well paid print workers go on strike in a recession and risk losing
their jobs? It is not something St Ives wants to test. But it may be doing
so in a few weeks' time.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
