<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JUL 92 / Brazil market tumbles after loan fraud claim
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTINA LAMB
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   RIO DE JANEIRO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE MAIN Brazilian stock market in Sao Paulo plummeted to close down 9.3 per
cent on the day yesterday, after an opposition senator said he could prove
evidence presented to a congressional inquiry into alleged presidential
corruption was fabricated.
Mr Eduardo Suplicy of the Workers' party had told Congress earlier in the
day that the fabrication was the work of Mr Claudio Vieira, a former senior
aide to President Fernando Collor. The accusation thickened the clouds over
the president's political future.
Mr Vieira told the inquiry on Monday that suspect payments into the bank
accounts of the president and his wife were the remains of a Dollars 5m
(Pounds 2.6m) loan Mr Vieira had raised in Uruguay in 1989, through which
gold had been bought to help fund the presidential electoral campaign that
year.
Bank documents before the inquiry last week suggested that the deposits,
running to Dollars 1m-plus, had been made by Mr Paulo Cesar Farias, Mr
Collor's friend and former campaign treasurer, who is under investigation
for alleged running of a bribes scheme.
Mr Suplicy claimed yesterday that Mr Vieira's evidence had been 'cooked up'
in recent meetings with Mr Farias and that the Uruguay loan documents were
typed last week in the office of Mr Alcides do Diniz Santos, a Sao Paulo
businessman. The senator said that Ms Sandra Fernandes de Oliveira,
secretary to Mr Diniz, was prepared to testify that she was at the meetings
and had typed the documents.
</TEXT>
