FT  30 JUL 92 / World Commodities Prices: Market report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GOLD see-sawed in a volatile and extended fixing session, climbing to
Dollars 359 a troy ounce and then tumbling to fix at a 12-day low of Dollars
356.20 in what appeared to be a move by US investment funds to extricate
themselves from an overheated market. The price closed in London at Dollars
356.85 an ounce, down Dollars 1.60 on the day. Dealers said the recent
strength of the gold market had been futures-driven on the back of US fund
buying, with the spot price lagging and weighed down by producer sales. At
the London Metal Exchange ALUMINIUM prices extended Tuesday's chart-inspired
technical fall to close at Dollars 1,313.50 a tonne, down Dollars 14 on the
day. A rally in London's COCOA futures market ran out of steam, apparently
without having attracted producer delling. The September price touched
Pounds 617 a tonne before slipping back to close at Pounds 612 a tonne, up
Pounds 13 on the day. Dealers thought a sharp fall in SUGAR futures might
have been sparked by talk of a sugar freight enquiry from Cuba to Morocco
which was interpreted by some as suggesting that sugar was beginning to
emerge from the Latin American country. The fall gathered momentum with
heavy stop-loss selling.
