FT  30 JUL 92 / International Company News: Commerzbank up 14.7% on brisk
credit demand
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WALLER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
COMMERZBANK, the smallest of Germany's big three banks and the first to
announce its figures for the first half of the year, yesterday reported
group profits - excluding securities trading results - up 14.7 per cent to
DM875m (Dollars 593.6m) to the end of June.
The bank said demand for credit from its domestic customers had been
'persistently brisk' during the six months and total lending volume rose by
2.4 per cent to DM161.7bn. Taking into account trading profits, total group
profits were up 17.5 per cent to DM975m.
Reflecting a slight improvement in the interest rate margin, to 1.94 per
cent across the group, net interest earnings rose by 12.3 per cent to
DM2.2bn. Because of a weaker trend in securities transactions, net
commission income fell by 2.2 per cent to DM633m.
Mr Martin Kohlhaussen, chief executive, warned that because of generally
difficult economic conditions the bank would probably have to make
provisions for individual loan losses. The effect of this would be countered
by extraordinary profits, chiefly via share disposals, he said.
Commerzbank has a large exposure to Olympia &amp; York, the ailing Canadian
property developer. It totals about DM560m, but Mr Kohlhaussen said
yesterday he felt the bank was unlikely to lose any money as a result. He
cited the bank's particularly good security, but also said he was heartened
by a recent visit to the Canary Wharf project in London's Docklands.
Mr Kohlhaussen gave no clue as to when the bank would hold its rights issue,
and sought to dampen speculation that it was discussing concrete proposals
for a share swap and co-operation agreement with Paribas of France.
</TEXT>
