<BYLINE>
   By JOHN BURTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SEOUL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SOUTH Korea's Ministry of Communications yesterday eliminated three of the
six consortia competing for the country's second mobile telephone franchise.
The winner is expected to be selected next month.
The ministry's selection board said Sunkyong, the country's seventh largest
business group, was the best qualified bidder on technical and financial
grounds, followed by Kolon and Pohang Iron and Steel Corporation (Posco).
The consortium led by Sunkyong includes the mobile telephone operators
Vodafone of the UK, GTE of the US and Hutchison Telecom of Hong Kong. Kolon,
a textile group, is being backed by British Telecom and Nynex of the US.
Posco, the world's third largest steelmaker is being supported by Pacific
Telesis of the US and Mannesmann of Germany.
</TEXT>
