</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JUL 92 / BAT sees sharp rise in pre-tax profits
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BOLGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
REDUCED mortgage indemnity losses helped BAT Industries, the tobacco and
financial services group, increase pre-tax profits by 55 per cent to Pounds
645m in the six months to June 30. Group revenue rose 5 per cent to Pounds
9.42bn.
Eagle Star, the group's insurance subsidiary, which has been hit heavily by
UK domestic mortgage losses, cut its first-half loses from Pounds 175m to
Pounds 47m.
The improvement in Eagle Star's general business allowed the group to use
more Advance Corporation Tax, cutting its tax rate from 57 per cent to 42
per cent.
Earnings per share more than doubled to 22.9p (10.1p) and the interim
dividend was lifted by 9 per cent to 14.6p.
Sir Patrick Sheehy, chairman, said the dividend increase was in line with
BAT's commitment to sustained dividend growth in excess of inflation, and
was a rate he expected to be at least maintained. BAT's shares closed 22p
higher at 756p.
The group said the 6 per cent increase in tobacco's trading profit to Pounds
475m reflected good performance in most domestic and export markets. Export
volumes grew 20 per cent and now account for a fifth of total cigarette
sales.
Trading profits from BAT's financial services businesses jumped to Pounds
252m from Pounds 83m. Farmers - the group's US arm - increased its
contribution from Pounds 168m to Pounds 204m.
During the second quarter, BAT said Farmers had become the fourth largest
property and casualty insurer in the US, having progressed from eighth
largest in 1988.
Sir Patrick said the sustained improvement in Eagle Star's underwriting
performance was especially encouraging, and had been aided by fair but
rigorous claims handling procedures.
Eagle Star made provisions for losses on its domestic mortgage business of
Pounds 49m, compared with Pounds 121m previously. Claims are triggered when
the proceeds from the sale of a repossessed property are less than the value
of the outstanding mortgage.
Sir Patrick said talks were continuing with building societies to see
whether they could agree a new system, whereby both insurers and building
societies groups 'shared the pain' of a fall in the house prices.
Lex, Page 18
</TEXT>
