<TEXT>
The Mary Whitehouse Experience was one of the funnier of the new wave comedy
programmes and three of its protagonists have been encouraged to write and
star in a new sit-com, Me, You and Him which receives its first outing on
ITV at 8.30. Inevitably it involves three youngish men, old school friends
now coping with real life - as a teacher, as an executive, and,
realistically, as an unemployed graduate.
More males on parade in Men Talk (Channel 4, 10.20). The opener, on sex,
aroused a good deal of media interest but this week the discussion centres
on the more mundane subject of male vanity. The problem with these frank
discussion programmes is that inevitably the participants are
unrepresentative exhibitionists.
Alan Bennett's words, Patricia Routledge's acting - who could ask for
anything more. Talking Heads provides the most civilised interlude in a duff
evening at 9.35 on BBC 2.
It is followed by the worthy Early Travellers in North America. Among the
commentators on the New World are Dickens, Thackeray and the Trollopes,
mother and son.
