<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JUL 92 / Lotus seeks to join the bicycle race: John Griffiths on how
the machine exciting Olympic hopes may be on the market soon
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GRIFFITHS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LOTUS Engineering, the consultancy design and engineering arm of General
Motors' troubled British sports-car subsidiary, is looking for a partner -
almost certainly in the aerospace industry - to produce and distribute a
roadgoing form of the 'supercycle' with which Chris Boardman of the UK is
dominating Olympic pursuit cycling.
It wants versions of the LotusSport pursuit cycle being used by Boardman,
offering a more traditional riding position but incorporating the basic
concept of a one-piece moulded monocoque frame, on world markets by early
next year.
Failure to do so may risk losing the benefit of the unprecedented - and
largely unexpected - publicity for the machine. 'We could lose the market to
makers of replicas which might look the same but lack its integrity and
performance, ' Lotus said yesterday.
Lotus plans to build a very limited number of machines over the next few
months at its Group Lotus headquarters in Hethel, Norfolk, which has
extensive facilities created originally for sports car production. The
machines will be built for top competition cyclists and will cost at least
Pounds 5,000 each.
Lotus might go on to build up to 1,000 somewhat less expensive units a year
 -forgoing carbon fibre at Pounds 330 a kilogramme and titanium at Pounds
150 a kilogramme - within its existing facilities.
It is mainly interested in finding a partner to which it can either license
the manufacture of a much higher volume of cheaper machines, a subcontractor
capable of building them - or taking part in a joint venture that might lead
to purpose-built facilities being created at Hethel.
Lotus Engineering does not expect initial derivatives of the 'supercycle' to
be sufficiently cheap to challenge manufacturers such as Raleigh in the
highest-volume sectors of the conventional cycle market. But it believes
there is scope for world-wide sales of many thousands a year towards the
upper end of the market.
The cycle is seen as presenting a potential challenge both to conventional
racing and quasi-racing cycles and to the fad for 'mountain' bikes, most of
which are unlikely ever to be used on a mountain but which nevertheless have
a strong lifestyle image for which buyers are prepared to pay upwards of
Pounds 600.
Although Lotus lays claim to having done substantial development work on the
cycle, and has invested some Pounds 125,000 in it, it is not a Lotus design.
It acquired the rights to the machine from its creator, Norwich-based
engineer Mr Michael Burrows, who had spent several years trying to interest
a number of cycle manufacturers in his concept.
The machine was unacceptable to the international cycle-racing authorities
when Mr Burrows first attempted to introduce it three years ago. The ban was
lifted last year.
</TEXT>
