<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JUL 92 / Accounting change on subsidiaries
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH COMPANIES will be forced to include more of their subsidiaries in
their group accounts under a new standard issued by the Accounting Standards
Board yesterday.
Accounting for subsidiary undertakings, the second financial reporting
standard (FRS) to come into effect, tightens criteria under the 1989
Companies Act for subsidiaries that must be consolidated or placed in group
accounts.
It comes into force for financial periods ending on or after December 23
this year.
Mr David Tweedie, ASB chairman, said the new standard was 'the foundation
stone for how we will deal with group accounts'.
He said that additional standards stipulating whether to consolidate joint
ventures, associated companies and off-balance-sheet companies would follow
over the next two years.
FRS 2 tightens one part of the 1989 Companies Act which allows subsidiaries
to be exempt from consolidation if they are very different from the parent
company.
The standard says that banking and insurance subsidiaries, as well as
non-profit entities, should now be consolidated, whereas previously they
could be exempted.
In principle, all subsidiaries should be consolidated when a parent company
can direct their financial and operating policies with a view to gaining
economic benefits from their activities.
The new standard also incorporates the third ruling issued by the ASB's
urgent issues task force earlier this year dealing with goodwill - the
difference between the purchase price of an acquisition and the value of its
net assets.
It states that any goodwill written off on the acquisition of a company must
be passed through the profit-and-loss account if the company is later sold,
unless it has already been written off against profits.
FRS 2. Accounting for subsidiary undertakings. Accountancy Books, PO Box
620, Central Milton Keynes MK9 2JX. Pounds 5.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 8
