<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JUL 92 / BR wins deal for shake-up on bargaining
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, CATHERINE MILTON and RICHARD TOMKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AFTER A year of intense but largely invisible, negotiation, British Rail has
won union agreement to abandon one of the most antique pieces of industrial
relations machinery - the 75-year-old Railway Staffs National Council.
That body, to which the most trivial disciplinary case could, theoretically,
be referred is being replaced with bargaining machinery based on BR's five
businesses and 30 profit centres.
At the top will be a Railway Joint Council, its remit restricted to pay and
basic conditions of employment for the 116,000 employees covered by
collective bargaining. At the business councils, more detailed matters such
as grading will be discussed, and at the profit centre councils almost
everything else.
Crucially for BR, there will be no 'reference up' from one level to the
higher level, although local disputes can be referred to the profit centre
councils. Individual grievances have been removed from the collective
bargaining machinery altogether.
Mr Gareth Hadley, BR's group employee relations manager, said the changes
were not merely a response to BR's more devolved structure and future
franchise-based system. 'Regardless of the current changes, we wanted to do
things in a different way with decision-making at the lowest possible level
and individual matters separated from the collective,' he said.
The unions, particularly the main rail union RMT, have been suspicious of
the potential 'fragmentation' of union power, and the RMT executive voted by
only a slender majority to accept. A similar attempt to change the
bargaining machinery lay behind the rail strike of 1989.
The unions remain concerned about arrangements for promotion and transfer
across businesses, but Mr Jimmy Knapp, leader of the RMT, said: 'We have
achieved our objectives within a trade union framework and with the BR board
committed to encouraging employees to join a union.'
The unions also say they have won improvements on earlier drafts of the
plan.
THE government will be ready to award cash grants for big rail projects as
part of its plans for rail privatisation, Mr John MacGregor, the transport
secretary, said yesterday, Richard Tomkins writes.
That is a significant departure from previous policy. So far, British Rail
has had to finance all its investment from revenues and loans. Grants have
been available only for loss-making commuter services and branch lines.
Speaking to business people in Aberdeen, Mr MacGregor said the track-owning
part of BR would have to fund most of its investment from charges to train
operators. Where projects would not earn returns large enough to justify
investment, the government would consider direct grants if the project
yielded wider benefits, such as relief of road congestion.
</TEXT>
