FT  30 JUL 92 / Tourists' outlay in England drops 4%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SKAPINKER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SPENDING by tourists in England fell by 4 per cent to Pounds 14.3bn last
year, the English Tourist Board said yesterday, Michael Skapinker writes.
Expenditure by UK tourists staying at their destination for a night or more
held up reasonably well, the board said, with revenues down 2 per cent to
Pounds 7.9bn. Spending by overseas visitors fell 9 per cent to Pounds 6.3bn.
Mr William Davis, board chairman, called on the government to take steps to
brighten up the English weekend in an attempt to attract more visitors.
He said: 'We support the idea of Sunday shopping but we also want to see
more attractions, theatres and restaurants open for business on Sunday and
we would like to see more sporting events, including racing.'
