FT  30 JUL 92 / UN chief endorses wider role in Croatia
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL LITTLEJOHNS and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK, GENEVA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR BOUTROS Boutros Ghali, the UN secretary-general, yesterday proposed a
further enlargement of the world body's responsibilities in Croatia despite
his earlier complaint that it was already over-extended in former
Yugoslavia.
Specifically, he endorsed 'with some misgiving' a recommendation by General
Satish Nambiar, the UN force commander, that his staff be authorised to
control civilian entry into UN-protected areas and exercise immigration and
customs functions at their borders.
Additionally, the secretary-general said there was a possibility of
establishing a UN military presence in the Prevlaka Peninsula, between
Dubrovnik and Serbia-Montenegro, to ensure that it stayed demilitarised. In
seeking a Security Council mandate, he stressed that his recommendations
illustrated how the situation in former Yugoslavia had brought about the
UN's involvement in 'quasi-governmental functions which go beyond normal
peace-keeping practice'.
Croatia and the Serbia have agreed on the release of all prisoners from
their conflict in Croatia, the International Committee of the Red Cross
(ICRC) said yesterday, Reuter reports from Geneva.
The ICRC said the Yugoslav prime minister, Mr Milan Panic, and the Croatian
deputy prime minister, Mr Mate Granic, had agreed to release the remaining
1,200 prisoners under ICRC auspices by August 7. The ICRC said it had
already helped secure the release of 4,000 prisoners from the conflict.
