<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUL 92 / Blue Arrow judge unlikely to resign
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Justice McKinnon, the Blue Arrow trial judge, is unlikely to resign in
spite of severe criticism by the Court of Appeal of his conduct of the
trial; nor is he likely to be dismissed.
Removing High Court judges from office is very difficult. They have the
right to hold office 'during good behaviour'. Only corrupt or criminal
behaviour is likely to put their job at risk.
Criticism of a judge for his handling of a case by a superior court is an
everyday occurrence. Although critical of Mr Justice McKinnon, the Appeal
Court did praise some aspects of his handling of the case, in particular the
lucidity of his summing up. He has already been replaced with Mr Justice
Brooke for the second and third parts of the Blue Arrow prosecution.
</TEXT>
