FT  29 JUL 92 / International Company News: IBM steps up job cuts plans
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN ZAGOR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
INTERNATIONAL Business Machines yesterday said at least 32,000 people would
take part in its voluntary workforce reduction programmes this year, above
its earlier estimates of about 20,000 job cuts, increasing the cost of the
programmes by about Dollars 1.2bn, writes Karen Zagor in New York.
IBM, which last year reported its first annual loss of Dollars 2.8bn after
charges on sales of Dollars 64.8bn, said it would recoup these costs over
the next 18 months through ongoing savings.
The company also indicated that changes were afoot at its personal computer
division. In response to reports that its PC business would be turned into a
wholly-owned subsidiary, IBM said it had been working to sharpen the focus
of its PC operations since December, 'and you will continue to see us
change'.
IBM would not comment about specific changes, but it has been working
towards increasing the autonomy and accountability of its business units
since December when it announced a broad restructuring of its worldwide
operations.
