<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUL 92 / International Company News: Asahi Glass pre-tax profits dip
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GORDON CRAMB
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ASAHI GLASS, Japan's leading glassmaker, yesterday disclosed a one-third
fall in interim pre-tax profits to Y22.7bn (Dollars 181.6m) from Y33.9bn,
and revised sharply downward its forecasts for the full year.
In a gloomy commentary accompanying the results, it said a decline in
consumer spending and a tighter rein on capital investment by manufacturers,
meant 'the Japanese economy began to take on aspects of a business
recession'.
Citing a production slowdown in the automotive industry and dull domestic
demand for television sets, two main markets the company supplies, it said
circumstances were 'harsh' and the outlook 'does not allow much room for
optimism.'
Asahi Glass is projecting pre-tax profits of Y48bn for 1992 as a whole, down
20.3 per cent from the previous year. Until yesterday it had been
forecasting a modest 2.9 per cent rise to Y62bn.
Sales for the first half to June dipped 2.2 per cent to Y487.6bn but are
expected by the company to edge 0.8 per cent ahead to reach Y1,030bn for the
full year. The previous forecast was for Y1,060bn in revenues.
Glass and construction materials, which account for half its total business,
showed sluggish sales except for energy-saving products and those with high
safety or design specifications.'
The company benefited from a 6.3 per cent rise in non-operating income to
Y14.6bn and a 15.4 per cent drop in its interest bill to Y3.6bn.
As planned, the interim dividend of Y5 a share includes a Y0.5 payment to
commemorate its 85th anniversary. It is being paid from net earnings per
share of Y10.49, down from Y17.14 last time when the payout was Y4.5.
</TEXT>
