<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUL 92 / International Company News: Allianz shares slip 3% on flat
results
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WALLER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MUNICH
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SHARES in Allianz, Germany's largest insurance group, fell 3 per cent
yesterday after the Munich-based group reported flat net profits for last
year and its first loss on its mainstream underwriting business.
Group net profits rose 4 per cent to DM1.05bn (Pounds 360m) on premium
income up 27 per cent to DM48.7bn. The underwriting result - the net of
premium income and claims paid before investment income - fell from a profit
of DM182m in 1990 to a loss of DM1.78bn.
Mr Henning Schulte-Noelle, chief executive, explained that the poor
underwriting performance was due to losses at Fireman's Fund, the large US
insurance company bought in 1990, and at Deutsche Versicherungs, the former
east German state insurance monopoly acquired for DM711m.
Another factor was the poor state of world insurance markets.
Mr Schulte-Noelle predicted that conditions would not improve substantially
during the current year. Premium income would rise to more than DM50bn, he
said, but underwriting profits would be hit by poor claims experience and
the effect of intense competition on premium income.
Deutsche Versicherungs and Fireman's Fund were consolidated for the first
time last year. This helped to boost group turnover but both made
underwriting losses of DM625m.
The underwriting figures were offset by a near-doubling in other income to
DM3.56bn, The main factors behind this were a DM929m contribution from
Fireman's Fund and extraordinary income of DM484m arising from the
restructuring of interests in Austria.
The shares fell by DM62 to close at DM1955.
The dividend is to be maintained at DM13.50 per share.
Lex, Page 18
