<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUL 92 / Former partner offers KIO Dollars 2.5bn for Spanish holdings
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER BRUCE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MADRID
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Javier de la Rosa, the Catalan financier who was an investment partner
with the Kuwait Investment Office in Spain for six years until last month,
has offered to create a consortium to buy Grupo Torras, the holding company
for the KIO's vast property and industrial empire in Spain, for Dollars
2.5bn (Pounds 1.3bn).
A provisional offer was made to the Kuwaiti finance minister, Mr Nasser
al-Rawdan, nearly two weeks ago, bypassing the KIO in London, whose
relations with Mr De la Rosa have become strained in the last six weeks.
Mr De la Rosa could not be reached yesterday. The offer requires an informal
response this week. Mr Ali Rashaid al-Bader, president of the KIO, declined
to say whether he was considering accepting it.
The bid is a challenge to the new management of the KIO, which, since taking
office in May, has indirectly accused Mr De la Rosa and former KIO leaders
of mismanaging Kuwait's assets in Spain. It also coincides with evidence
that the KIO wants to sell its Spanish portfolio.
The offer creates a dilemma for the KIO. If it does not accept, it may have
tacitly conceded that Torras is worth more than Dollars 2.5bn and thus risk
supporting the view of former KIO managers that the Spanish assets are
fundamentally sound.
Since the mid-1980s, the KIO has spent Dollars 3.7bn buying Spanish
companies and creating its biggest chemicals, foods and paper groups, and
one of its most dynamic property developers.
But the KIO assets have been shaken by the collapse of the chemicals
division, Ercros. It filed for protection from its creditors earlier this
month owing more than Dollars 2bn after the KIO refused to inject fresh
capital into its fertiliser operations. Stock in two other Torras quoted
companies has fallen sharply.
The offer involves a Dollars 400m payment followed by two further payments
of Dollars 1bn each over the next two years. If the Kuwaitis signal interest
by the end of this week, a formal offer, to expire on October 25, would be
made.
Mr De la Rosa's role in a consortium would be limited because of the large
amounts involved. He promised to supply guarantees from reputable banks.
</TEXT>
