<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUL 92 / British Aerospace poised to unveil strategy for recovery:
Group expected to focus on profitable core activities
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS, Aerospace Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR John Cahill, the new chairman of British Aerospace, is expected to unveil
next month his recovery strategy for Britain's biggest manufacturing company
aimed at refocusing the group on its profitable core military aircraft and
Airbus activities.
Mr Cahill, former BTR chief executive, will make his first public policy
statement as BAe's chairman when the company announces its financial results
for the first half of its current fiscal year next month, aerospace industry
officials and City analysts said yesterday.
The strategy of refocusing the company on core activities is also expected
to entail heavy asset write-offs which some City analysts believe could
amount to around Pounds 750m as well as a possible dividend cut.
BAe is experiencing difficult trading conditions in its main markets and
activities, and the City expects the group to report a loss in the first
half and for the whole of fiscal 1992.
Analysts estimate an operating loss of between Pounds 40m and Pounds 50m for
the full year before provisions.
The write-offs, and fears of a dividend cut, depressed BAe's share price
which yesterday fell a further 10p to 180p. This is less than half the price
of the rights issue of 380p last winter and less than a third of the share
price of 576p 12 months ago.
BAe's share price was also hit by a report that the European Commission
might require the UK government to recoup interest on Pounds 44.4m of aid it
paidto BAe when the company took over the Rover car group in 1988.
The EC is expected to issue in September a new order for repayment by BAe of
the Pounds 44.4m 'sweeteners' and possibly interest which it considers
illegal state support. But City analysts yesterday suggested the EC
initiative was relatively modest in the face of BAe'sdeeper structural
problems.
Mr Cahill has already introduced stricter disciplines on capital spending
and is expected to accelerate efforts to cut the cash drain from
unprofitable or non-core activities.
A priority is a solution to the company's loss-making regional jet business.
BAe has been struggling to find international partners for its regional jet
oper-ations.
UK aerospace industry officials said yesterday the company was increasingly
likely to shelve its BAe 146 regional jet programme if it failed to find
partners.
One hint that the the company's regional aircraft operations are to be
reshaped imminently was the decision to transfer all 146 product support
operations to BAe's Airbus division. This would ensure continued product
support for 146 operators in the event of an decision to shut down 146
production.
In spite of doubts over the future of the European Fighter Aircraft (EFA)
programme in which BAe is a leading partner, the company's military aircraft
activities continue to be regarded as one of its main strengths together
with its 20 per cent stake in the European Airbus large airliner consortium.
