<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUL 92 / Allied and Carlsberg to link up: MMC attaches conditions to
joint brewing venture in UK
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP RAWSTORNE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ALLIED-LYONS and Carlsberg indicated yesterday that the Pounds 510m merger
of their UK brewing operations would go ahead after modifications to meet
the demands of the Monopolies and Mergers Commission.
Nine months after the UK drinks, food and retailing group and the Danish
brewer announced their intention to create a joint force in the UK beer
market, the MMC recommended by a four-to-one majority that the merger should
only proceed if:
Carlsberg-Tetley, the merged company, undertook not to worsen the terms of
beer supplies to Carlsberg's existing customers among regional and local
brewers and independent wholesalers during the next three years.
The term of the supply agreement between Carlsberg-Tetley and Allied pubs
was reduced from seven to five years.
Allied amended its tenancy or lease agreements so that its tied pubs would
be free after two years to buy up to half their annual lager requirements
from suppliers of their own choice.
The European Commission, which conducted a separate inquiry, set similar
conditions for the merger.
Mr Roy Moss, chairman of Allied's brewing division, and Mr Michael Iuul,
Carlsberg International's managing director, said in a joint statement: 'We
are firmly of the view that the proposed joint venture is the best strategy
for both companies.
'When we have explored the practicalities of the conditions suggested in
greater detail, we are confident that we will find a mutually acceptable way
forward in the best interests of our shareholders, customers and employees.'
The most onerous condition would appear to be the obligation on Allied to
free its tenants to open their pubs to other lagers after two years. In
practice, however, few pubs would be likely to change brands unless faced
with extreme customer dissatisfaction.
The MMC found the merger would have positive and detrimental effects on
competition.
Carlsberg-Tetley would be a more effective brewer, the MMC said, with a
better balanced portfolio of brands than Allied and Carlsberg separately,
and able to compete more vigorously with the two biggest brewers, Bass and
Courage.
Since Carlsberg owned no pubs, the merger would not increase the number
nationally with tied beer supplies.
Against this, the MMC concluded that the merger would increase concentration
in lager production. Carlsberg-Tetley would have a 21 per cent share of the
market and the three largest brewers would account for 67 per cent.
Allied-Lyons and Carlsberg, Report on the proposed joint venture. HMSO.
Pounds 11.10.
Brewers keep their places at the bar, Page 19
