<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUL 92 / PM backs Lamont on Community VAT deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH and ANDREW HILL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN MAJOR entered the row about the UK's agreement to an EC minimum rate
of value added tax with a vigorous defence yesterday of the deal struck by
Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor.
Ministers sought to brush aside Tory Euro-sceptic charges that the move
diminished UK sovereignty, insisting the agreement was vital to ensure
completion of the single market.
Mr Major said VAT had been a Community matter since the Treaty of Rome, and
emphasised that Monday's deal did not affect zero-rated goods and services.
He also highlighted the benefits for the Scotch whisky industry.
Mr Major's remarks came against a background of Tory wrangling on the deal.
While Mr Lamont called suggestions that the UK had ceded sovereignty 'a
complete scare, and a very silly, silly season story', Mr Nick Budgen, a
Euro-sceptic, said the chancellor was 'justifying his betrayal of the
British constitution on the basis that he has served a commercial interest'.
The agreement received a mixed reception from business leaders. The
Institute of Directors warned that it should not be taken as a precedent for
EC intervention in corporation tax and was a compromise 'which should not be
presented as a victory'. But the Confederation of British Industry and the
British Chambers of Commerce welcomed it as an important step towards
completing the single market.
The provisional agreement could still founder on Spanish and French
objections. Spain wants Britain to change the name of British-made sherry,
or grant equal tax treatment to Spanish sherry.
France wants a French-style 'control duty' on all EC-produced wine, a higher
harmonised excise duty on mineral oils, and a standard VAT rate on
'agricultural products' such as flowers.
VAT harmony, Page 2 Editorial Comment, Page 16
