<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUL 92 / Observer: Merged out
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Unions, like companies, often discover that mergers have unexpected costs.
Officials of the former print union Sogat, which last year merged with the
NGA print union to form the GPMU, estimate that redundancy payments to
former Sogat officials whose faces did not fit have reached about Pounds
330,000. Brenda Dean, the 49-year-old former Sogat leader, and most
prominent casualty of the merger, has pocketed Pounds 148,000.
The London Machine Branch of GPMU, a former Sogat stronghold, is so alarmed
by such figures, and by the NGA's domination of the merged union, that it
has called for a special conference to discuss Dean's departure. But Alf
Elderton, the branch secretary, admits that the response has been relatively
cool. 'People say a conference would cost too much money,' he says.
Tony Dubbins, the GPMU general secretary, defends the pay-outs on the
grounds that the merger has saved Pounds 1m from the joint wages bill of the
two unions. The pay-out to Dean - overshadowed only by the Pounds 220,000
paid to Clive Jenkins by the white collar union MSF - appears to have been
part of the merger agreement.
</TEXT>
