<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUL 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONY THORNCROFT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BBC2's Screenplay at 9.00 is 'Man to Man', a one woman monologue by Manfred
Karge, which was first admired as a stage play. Tilda Swinton, an
accomplished actress who seems doomed to play male characters, is the German
housewife who, to survive in Nazi Germany, takes on her husband's identity
after his death and plays out the role for over 40 years.
Anyone who thinks that all Jackie Collins' sex and shopping novels read the
same will be unsurprised that two of them, Lucky and Chances, have been
merged into one mini series which starts on ITV at 9.00 and sprawls over
much of the next two nights to provide six hours of escapist viewing. Mind
you they share a heroine, Lucky, a gangster's daughter.
Collins, upset at unsympathetic adaptations of her work, has written the
screenplay and produced this tale of passion, power and greed.
Has the demise of the Soviet Union left the CIA without a role? Not
according to its new director, Robert Gates, who maps out a future for
himself heading an Agency that ferrets out data on narcotics, terrorists and
nuclear proliferation. (BBC 1, 9.30).
</TEXT>
